On Monday I mentioned I was offline for 2 weeks fighting a massive architectural fire. Here is the exact RCA of how our own auto-scaler DDOS'd our database.

Our stack looked like textbook "Best Practice: EKS", 15 microservices, Managed Postgres and an HPA (Horizontal Pod Autoscaler) set to trigger at 70% CPU.

The fatal flaw was synchronous inter-service communication. Our Checkout Service made a synchronous HTTP call to our Auth Service, which then queried the database.

When a 4x traffic spike hit at 2:00 AM:
1. The Auth DB queries slowed down under load.
2. Checkout HTTP requests timed out, triggering an immediate retry (with zero exponential backoff).
3. Auth was suddenly handling the actual traffic spike PLUS 3x retries from upstream.

Then, Kubernetes made it lethal. The HPA saw Auth CPU spike to 90% and did exactly what it was told: It spun up 20 new pods. But every new pod immediately opened 10 new direct connections to Postgres.

Within seconds, we hit the max_connections limit. The database locked up entirely. We didn't die from the traffic spike; we died from our own retry logic and auto-scaler.

On Monday, I’ll share exactly what we did at 3:00 AM to stop the bleeding.

